post_text: Student Item Pick-Up: Beginning today student items will be available for pick up and we ask that one person from each family come to pick up items. We have designated days for each family: Monday, May 11th will be for families with the last name A-H, Tuesday, May 12th will be families with the last name I-P and Wednesday, May 13th will be families with the last name Q-Z. Pick up will take place from 1 pm â€“ 5 pm each of these days. Medications will also be available for pick up during this time. The representative for each family will come to the front of the building where bins will be available for library books and textbooks to be dropped off and student items will be distributed. We will have the sidewalk marked in order to maintain social distancing of 6 ft., we ask that you please cooperate with us in maintaining this order.

Dear Cole R-1 Families -

We want to let you know that Cole R-1 is closely monitoring this rapidly-changing situation regarding the spread of the coronavirus. Naturally, it is a concern when we hear about health-related events like this. While there are currently no known cases of the virus in our area, we are proactively working to have a plan should it be needed. Please be assured that the health and safety of our students and staff is always our top priority. Please read the attached letter.

Thank you

Perry Gorrell, Superintendent

post_text:
I had the pleasure of chaperoning a youth trip with my church for middle school students. Ethan Strobel attended that trip. While we were at McDonald's, he noticed a man that was sitting alone and playing a game by himself. He started a conversation with him and found out he had a rough life. He took time to hear his story. He also bought the man coffee. Ethan and a few friends went in together and gave him some money. What a great way to show kindness and compassion to a man. I am so proud of the way he helped someone else.

Sincerely,
Andrea Stockman, Elem/MS Counselor

post_text:
In the beginning of the year, we talked about kindness as a character trait. Kate Oligschlaeger noticed a student that wore the same clothes and ate every bite of their food at breakfast and lunch. Kate came to me and asked if her family could buy the student some things. I told her that is a wonderful idea and she did just that!! Her family brought in some much needed clothes, shoes and helped this student so much!! They had a smile for days because of the kindness that was shared by this family. Thank you, Kate for being that star student and helping another family in need!! Great work!! We are proud of you!!

Sincerely,
Andrea Stockman
